Hexapodid crabs were often regarded as having sternal male genital openings (
Barnard 1950: 283
, key; 
Balss 1957: 1658
). The family was assigned either to the Thoracotremata (or Catometopa) (
Guinot 1978
provisionally; 
Schram 1986
; 

Schweitzer 
et al
. 2000

; von Sternberg & Cumberlidge 2001) or to the Heterotremata (
Guinot 1979
; 
Saint Laurent 1989
; 
Guinot & Richer de Forges 1997
; 
Guinot & Bouchard 1998
; 
Martin & Davis 2001
), the latter implying a true coxal condition of the male openings.
